1. Export types and syntax
- Named exports: export let|const|var name; export function fn(){}; export { name1, name2 as alias };
- Default exports: export default expression; export default function(){}; export default class {};
- Aggregating exports: export * from "module"; export { name } from "module"; export * as ns from "module";

2. Named exports semantics
- A module can have multiple named exports; exported names must be unique per module.
- Named exports are statically linked; importers must refer to the exported name (or rename via import { name as alias }).
- Export declarations are not subject to temporal dead zone rules; you may declare export { x } before x is declared locally.

3. Default export semantics
- A module may have at most one default export. Default export can be any expression, declaration, or anonymous function/class declaration.
- Default export can be imported with any local name: import anyName from './mod.js';

4. Re-exporting (export from) semantics and caveats
- export { name } from "mod" re-exports named exports without binding them locally.
- export * from "mod" re-exports all named exports from mod, but not the default export.
- Conflicting star exports result in the name being omitted; importing that name from the aggregator throws a SyntaxError.
- To re-export a default export: export { default as name } from "mod" or export { default } from "mod" (re-exported as default).
- export { name as "string name" } allows non-identifier exported names.

5. Module execution and declaration ordering
- export declarations are only declarations and do not access values at module evaluation time; therefore export { x }; const x = 1; works because export is a declaration only.
- Duplicate exported names or multiple default exports cause SyntaxError and module evaluation will fail.

6. Usage notes and constraints
- Modules must be loaded as type="module" in browsers; cannot use file:// URLs with modules due to CORS.
- Use export aggregators (barrel modules) to centralize exports; watch for conflicting names across aggregated modules.

